e>William</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Jennings</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>CO_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF019491%2F1"><gtr:id>D0004EF9-6766-48DB-B79F-59BFFC5EA8FC</gtr:id><gtr:title>ECRP07: collaboration led by Christoffer Green-Pedersen, University of Aarhus, Denmark - Legislative policy agendas in the UK</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F019491/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This project aims to find out the amount of attention policy-makers in the UK pay over time to particular policy areas, such as the environment, transport, education and defence.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/p>

&lt;p>It focuses upon the legislature - with legislation (ie Acts of Parliament) and Prime Minister's Questions (ie weekly questioning of the Prime Minister in the House of Commons) as the principal measures of attention. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>It aims to create a record of the interest of British government and its legislators in questions of policy since 1960.&amp;nbsp; The project uses a UK version of a widely used Policy Agendas code frame, developed for the USA (see &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.policyagendas.org/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;>http://www.policyagendas.org/&lt;/a>).&lt;/p>

&lt;p>It will report frequencies of the 21 major policy topics to provide a measure of change or stability in political attention and carry out regression analysis to examine the causes of agenda change. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>It is a project covering the UK as it will replicate this approach for data from the Scottish Parliament to find out whether attention to agendas differs between the devolved Scottish political system and UK Parliament in Westminster.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>

